description.text: For those who keep getting the (hotent/heatbreak area) end of their teflon tubing to melt, causing the filament to clog, some are purchasing Capricorn PTFE filament. I'm betting that anyone who is cutting a new end to their filament are totally replacing the entire length of the tubing (from extruder to the hotend's heatbreak). What a waste.

Printer:

CR-10

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.20

Infill:

30

Notes:

For your Raft: You only need a 3mm cushion distance (outside the coupler).

With this coupler, you can now save most of your current tubing and only cut a piece of tubing that goes inside the hotend and stick out of the top one inch. That's enough to fit this coupler with enough tubing to spare. For those who aren't using Capricorn tubing and experience melting of the tubing within the hotend, replacing a short piece is much less expensive than replacing the entire length of the tubing.

The inside diameter is enough to make the tubing a nice tight fit. It your printed coupler's inside diameter (hole for the tubing to be inserted) is smaller, you can use a 5/32 drill bit.

*** Caution: Only drill half way in ( 11mm ) because there's a break in the center so each side of the tubing fits equally within the coupler.

Making a perfect size hole for the tubing....

.....a 5/32 drill bit will create a perfect size for the tube to fit into and maintain its position.

*** For those who experience the Bowden tube slipping out of the collar, place two (check the photo) zipties, one on the collar, the other on the upper PTFE tube, to keep the Capricorn PTFE from pushing the collar away. Use pliers to grab the ziptie to cinch down the tie. Cut excess tie.

Designed using....

...Windows 10 3D Builder. A simple cylinder and insert cylinder (for the feflon tube to reside) for subtraction.

description.text:
This six-file 3D printable model gives a rare view into the Earth-based counterpart of many an interplanetary spacecraft. Models of spacecraft are popular, but the vehicles they represent are incomplete and of no use without the tons of sttel and concrete and systems that make up Earth-based stations like this one.
This is a 1:250 scale model of a 34-meter diameter Beam Waveguide (BWG) Deep Space Station. It prints easily without needing any support material or rafting. It illustrates the antenna's mechanical structure and its microwave beam-waveguide system. It shows correctly how the dish rotates in azimuth and elevation above-grade, while the waveguide tubes articulate to reflect radio signals to and from the receivers and transmitters, which are located below-grade (not represented in the model).
The BWG stations are the newest design in NASA's Deep Space Network (DSN). There are several in place in the Deep Space Communications Complexes at Goldstone, California, Madrid, Spain, and Canberra, Australia, and more ar being built today. Four of them, when electronically arrayed, can reproduce the gain and performance of one 70-meter diameter station. Together, these exquisitely precise ground stations comprise the thousands of tons of concrete and steel which constitute the "other end" of so many interplanetary spacecraft. This model was designed to reproduce key aspects of a DSN station at least an order of magnitude better than the free downloadable paper version.
There are six print files (.stl), which contain a total of ten parts to be printed using white ABS plastic, about 65.3 cm3 in all. The parts fit together easily and are to be welded in place using a few drops of acetone. The main reflector piece takes a good bit of careful bending and clamping and waiting after it's been printed. As designed, it will unfortunately NOT print on a platform smaller than 8X8 inches.
The main reflector requires an 8X8-inch build platform. Printer setting details and illustrated assembly instructions may be fond here: http://spacecraftkits.com/BWG.html

description.text:
I couldn't find my Niece's favorite shopkins anywhere 3d modeled.. so I took this from a picutre and rendered the whole thing from scratch, i don't know exactly how close it is, but it looks like the actual shopkins. This one stands 120mm tall, and is a coin bank with a slot-fit cylinder in the bottom. It's for her christmas present, and i haven't printed it yet, but i would suggest printing in halves with supports (like included models)..

Happy printing!

from picture to 3d object

If you ever need to convert a picture into a 3d model, you've got some work ahead of you! but... if you want to, edit the picture to break down the edges so you can fake a "bump map" for the edges. After that, import the picture into your slicer directly (as of Cura 2.4) and then export it as an stl.. it will have some settings things that will be helpful to take those initial steps to making a 3d model. The next thing to think about is the actual "3rd dimension"... in my case, the picture included feet and hands, but they probably didn't go from the front to the back directly. In whatever case you find yourself, do whatever you're comfortable with, but remember that you get a LITTLE license when you're adding a whole dimension.

Lastly, in my case, as in any case, you think of "faces" of your end model. My picture had "popcorn" on top, but it was likely that the popcorn would actually be receding into the middle from bottom to top. My total model has 9 main "faces" and i took that into account when modeling each piece from the source picture...

again, good luck and happy printing!

This is a hollow 20mm cube for calibrating your 3D printer! Cubes are hugely popular to calibrate axis linear travel, but this hollow design also allows you to also calibrate bridging and extrusion flow, all while cutting down the amount of time and filament used for your print. It has 1mm thick walls on all sides, measures exactly 20mm on all the outer faces, and has a hollow interior, all without the need of any support material.
Head over to the 'Instructions' tab to get started.
Got the cube to print nicely? Check out my Bridge Calibration Object for even more bridging calibration.
Wanna remix it? Fire up 'Customizer' and make a cube of your very own!

• Download and print. (without support material)
  • Measure all sides and adjust stepper motors in your firmware accordingly. This is done by dividing 20mm by your measurement for that axis, then multiplying your stepper's settings by the result.
  • Inspect the roof and adjust the bridging speed. (I had to slow mine down to 10 mm/sec to get a flat roof.)
  • You could also stop a print half-way to measure the cube's wall thickness so that you can fine-tune your extruder steps.
  • Repeat these steps until you have a perfect 20mm cube.
  • Post a picture showing off your cube under the "I Made One" tab!

comments.author: TheGusman

comments.text:
No, it is not normal for there to be a bead on the corner. The problem is a misconfiguration with slic3r, not your actual printer, basically what's happening is the extruder retracts a little bit of filament during each layer change and then spits out a little too much at the start of the next layer, hence the reason why the bead stayed at the same corner each time. You can fix this problem by going to Printer Settings>Extruder1 (or something like that) on expert mode in Slic3r, and changing some of the retraction settings. I would recommend starting by enabling/disabling retraction on layer change, and changing the "extra length on restart" value to zero. If those fixes don't help much, your extruder is probably miscalibrated and you should calibrate it using Triffid Hunter's Calibration Guide
I hope this helps, best of luck to you!

description.text:
I remixed migthynozzle's linear bearings https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2202854 to get rid of the original aluminum bearing holders. I have an Anet A8 and their quality is horrible sice the screwholes are sometimes more than 1mm away from their intended position.

Since I really like the IGUS like bearings, I took them and added a holder with which they can be used for bothe the x- and the y-axis.

Their size is LM8UU. If you need a differnt size, please add a commet and I'll see what I can do.

The holders can be attached by adding 4 M4 nuts with a height of 3mm to the corresponding holes.

If you have any problems or further questions, please write me a comment.

If you like it, you may also check out my other Anet A8 and 3d printing things:

  • Customizeable Cooling Fan Blades
  • Filament Guides for the Anet A8 in 6 variations (0°, 45°, 90°) Vertical and Horizontal
  • Anet A8 - Original X Axis Mounts V2
  • Spoolhoder tube to lower rotational resistance (requires two axle bearings)
  • Cable Clip (Anet like)
  • Improved Customizeable Anet A8 E3Dv6 Mount with 40mm Fan Mount

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

50 %

Notes:

To be able to print bearings that can be actually used, you need a highly calibrated printer. The printer should be able to print with an accuracy of approximatly 0.1 mm in x- and y- direction and no z-wobble or something like this. This is only achievable if your belts are tight enough, so you will probably need to print some other improvements first.

Since I have no idea how to get this 3d-Model into OpenSCAD, the model is not customizeable like the one I remixed. Since there is basically only one size that has to be varied, which is the inner diameter of the bearing, I added stl-files for diamters between 8 mm and 8.5 mm. If you need a larger or a smaller one, please write a comment.

The screwholes and the holes for the nuts are 0.2 mm larger than they are supposed to be to compensate for printing tolerances. Their heigh is also 0.2 mm smaller than the original one.

Tuning

You should start printing a bearing with an inner diameter near 8.25 mm. After it finished, take a rod and try how well it is fitting. If its too loose, print a smaller diameter, if its to tight print a larger diameter until you find the best fitting one. If none of the diameters fits perfectly, print the next smaller one and push the rod through it multiple times. By that you remove a small ammount of material and suddenly the bearing will fit perfectly.

If your printer suffers from z- wobble or other inconsistencies between the different layers, you need to fix that first, otherwise you wont reach the required accuracy.

  • Lüfterplatte:
    Die Platte hat die passenden Bohrungen für diesen Lüfter -> BE QUIET PURE WINGS 2 92mm PC-LÜFTER - Conrad Aktikelnummer 1170667 - EAN 4260052183380.

I was asked to extend this to a 5-section and 6-section thing. Not sure how useful it will be for larger pills, but here they are.

This is a set of section dividers for 16 dram and 13 dram pill bottles. There are 3 pieces required for each divider -- the divider body, the selection cover and the button.

The first picture is an assembled 16 dram, 4-section pill bottle. Notice how not having sides on the dividers allows you to see which pill you are selecting.

Notes:

After printing the selector covers, make sure you let them cool before you remove them from the printer bed, or they will bend!

After printing, use a razor blade to trim a lead-in taper on the pin on top of the divider body. Then, drill the selection cover a little undersized so that it snaps into position. Drill the button and press it over the cover for a nice tight fit. If the parts are a little sloppy, you can attach the button by pressing the top of the pin down with a warm (not too hot) soldering iron. Or, you can make my handy-dandy Filament Rivet Tool (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2755673) and make a nice rivet to hold the button. Note that the 2-section divider requires an extra button installed below the cover in order to provide the cover some extra support.

If the tolerance of the bottles and dividers are such that they are a little loose, then simply put a drop of model car cement on the bottom of the divider when you put it in the bottle.
With multiple sections, it's hard to pick out just the pill you need so that's why I designed a selector top. It functions a lot like a spice bottle. Simply twist the cover to the pill you want.

description.text:
I modified the original case by kleinerELM.

Changes
  • Added a pocket for a 4 pin style BME280 - may need a drop of glue for fastening the PCB
  • Reduced the tube orifice to 9mm for a snug fit and removed it on the right side
  • Reduced the bottom USB cable inlet
  • Enlarged the weather protection shield on the left (+20mm)
  • Moved the tube orifice 5mm to the rear side (not verified, see below)
What failed
  • Added covers above the wall mount holes to make the rear side weatherproof - failed as the SDS011 needs this space - ripped them out and closed the wall mounts with Bondic UV adhesive. Thus they were removed from the model. If you decide to add them again keep in mind to move everything inside up as much as those covers may consume in height.
  • Added a perforated cylinder between the left weather protection shield and the air inlet with 1mm holes and 1mm land between them. Without internal supports this was also a failure and has been removed.
Conclusion

Most changes were done because I wanted to make it more difficult for insects to settle down in the case (but I'm sure they'll do so nonetheless) and to protect the BME280.

The tube orifice was moved 5mm to the back as it was not in line with the inlet of my SDS011. The 5mm were guessed and I've not yet printed the case after changing it as the current one still gets the job done. Please let me know what your experiences are.

I really liked the new MK3 extruder head. Soooo, I decided to reverse engineer the MK3 extruder and x-carriage assembly to make it fit the MK2/MK2s. My main motivation was the clean mounting of the Noctau fan and the new nozzle blower.

Things I changed from the MK3 assembly:

1) Moved the motor mounting screws over a bit to accommodate the existing filament driver.

2) Created holes to mount the idler and made space for it. Had to modify the idler a bit to fit properly inside the new extruder body.

3) Had to make quite a bit of changes on the x-carriage to make it work with the existing wires and the end stop. I removed some things and added some holes for the zip ties. I didn't want to use the back plate as it was easier to just get rid of it. TBH, it's unnecessary to create an extra piece just to hold your wires up in the air nicely...

4) Expanded the PINDA probe hole to fit the MK2s probe.

5) Removed the filament sensor mounting.

6) Modified a bunch of other small stuff along the way to make the whole thing work.

EDIT1: Updated the idler. Forgot to cut the hole all the way through.
EDIT2: Updated the x-carriage to fit with the MK3 x-carriage cover. Much better cable management, I take back what I said above.

title: Adjustable cam for use with a limit switch

description.text: This is an adjustable cam for setting the stop points of our kicker on our 2014 FIRST Robotics Competition Robot.  It allows us to adjust the operation of the robot without replacing parts.  By using the cam alongside a limit switch, the kicker will have an ensured stopping point when in operation. The camâs unique shape allows the metal tab on the limit switch to be easily activated while an indent on the cam rotates over it.  A rocker cap can also be placed on the limit switch to make it easier to roll over.

The file names are color coded to match the photo.  Of course, use whatever colors you like!  The adjustable cam goes on the hub first, then the fixed cam.  #6 hex head screws can be used to hold the part together.  The hub is designed to work with 1/2 inch keyed shaft.  
This design allows for the adjustable cam to be manipulated to adjust the position of where the limit switch will engage.  For our application, this was to let the robot know the kicker was in position to kick!  
The rocker switch can be slid over the metal lever of a limit switch to give the cam an easy piece to roll against.

Netfabb, Cura, and Kisslicer all identify copious errors in the solid-wall versions, and when sliced, half the number digit pieces appear to be separated from the solid wall by a couple of tenths of a mm. Net is that the solid walls need to be thicker, so they intersect better with the digits.

A Simpler Construction of Moineau Pump Stator via CNC Milling

Novel composition of a stator designed such that it can be easier to built --hopefully in metal via Milling CNC machines as depicted in the picture.

It is based on the decomposition of the stator in one building block (or base). It allows to reduce considerably its dimensions to extrude plastic at 180 oC, or more, using desktop 3D printers and control the positive displacement of viscous material from plastic PET bottles.

Our variant of stator is easy to built and clean. More details at: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.addma.2017.08.015 (work is in progress).

title: Square Terminal for Galaxy Luna (Straight Talk)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a credit card terminal for use with a Square Reader -- (http://www.squareup.com)

Additional Hardware Required:

  • Samsung Galaxy Luna Cell Phone - Link
  • Square Reader - Link
  • 1 Foot TRRS Audio Extension Cable - Link (Tested & Works)
  • Small zip ties - Link
  • Stylus Pens - Link
  • Lanyard for Stylus Pens - Link (Optional)

Software:

  • Square App - Link
  • MobiLock - Link (Optional, used to lockdown the system)
  • Buttons Remapper - Link - (Optional, used to disable the menu button)

Assembly:

  • Print out all of the parts.
  • Print out 2 or 3 of "Terminal Shim.stl". (I needed 2).
  • Place 2 of the shims under the phone. (use 3 if needed).
  • Route the charger cord through the hole on the bottom of the base, then plug the cord into the phone.
  • Lay the phone down into the base.
  • Screw the cover down using 4pcs M3 x 16mm Screws.
  • Insert the Square Reader into the slot on the base. Push firmly until it's fully seated (flush with the top).
  • Plug in the TRRS Cable to the Square Reader through the bottom of the base.
  • Route the TRRS Cable first, through the cable slots on the bottom of the base.
  • Route the USB Charger Cable, through the cable slots on the bottom of the base.
  • Insert zip-ties into the small slots on the bottom of the base. Secure the wires using zip-ties.
  • Plug in the TRRS Cable into the phone.

Note: The power and volume button will no longer be accessible. This is designed for the phone to be turned on and plugged in at all times.

It is full of small holes that you will not be able to clean adequately. Bacteria would flourish. Never mind the issue of food-safe filament.

The Universal Socket Prosthetic tackles the challenge of limb differences from a completely new angle. We aim to reframe prosthetic design, allowing anyone to create a customized prosthetic system that they can adapt and use over long periods of time. Rather than attempting to design a “jack-of-all-trades” arm, our socket system uses varying custom attachments to accomplish a wide range of tasks. It consists of a mesh, sandwich interface with the residual limb, combined with a hexagonal socket that accepts a corresponding shaft on attachments. Users can resize the mesh to fit different arms, and the attachment system allows for easy development of new components with simple CAD skills.

The system is particularly well suited for children: its affordability distinguishes it from most prosthetics, which are complex and costly to make yet need to be replaced frequently as children grow. Furthermore, its ease of creation and editing allows for active use as kids grow, break things, and explore new activities. Each component of the design is large, colorful, and does not require high dexterity, so that even children younger than five can properly operate it. Our research and interviews with parents found that children did not care if the hand is skin-colored, or about the precision of the engineering. They want something that looks fun, is easy to use, and keeps them from getting left out of the activities they enjoy. Based on these insights, hobbies and sports have become a focal point of our work.

Our prosthetic can attach to anything the user wants by adding a simple 3D-printed hexagon to any object, from a baseball bat to a painter’s palette. The specific functionalities that this system enables are key to its value: while more complex prosthetics are generally designed to carry out a variety of tasks, they often do not perform any one task exceptionally well. By distributing high-level functions across a modular system, our design aims to equip prosthetic users with a toolkit for effectively and enjoyably participating in a wide range of activities. While at least one other company has pursued a similar approach to prosthetic design, specializing in sports and musical attachments, these products are very complex (which would make it difficult for kids to use) and expensive to buy and replace. Our design aims to lower these barriers, bringing high-performing prosthetics to a broader audience.

The Universal Socket Prosthetic has enormous potential for accessible impact, and we hope that a diverse community will join us in continuing to build on this concept — allowing anyone with a limb difference to explore new hobbies with ease and flexibility.

The project was created as part of a mechanical engineering and bioengineering course, Designing for the Human Body, taught by Grace O’Connell and held at the Jacobs Institute for Design Innovation at UC Berkeley. The Universal Socket Prosthetic was developed in conjunction with the nonprofit Claws from Carter. We worked with the organization’s founder, Michael Campos, whose son Carter was born with a limb difference. The direct impact that our idea could have on Carter’s life has driven our passion throughout the project process. It was important to make the product not only functional and cost-effective, but also fun to use — at the end of the day, it did not matter how good our dimensioning and tolerancing was if Carter did not love using our design. As we faced time and budget constraints in our design process, we also employed lightweight methods of testing our design: for example, to optimize the weight reduction with structural strength without wasting days on multiple 3D prints, we first laser cut designs out of paper as structural analogues. While this method was far from perfect, ultimately our rapid-prototyping approach, paired with a close collaboration with end-users, led to a functional and appealing prototype. We believe this testing method can be used in future design processes that are constrained on time and budget, reducing barriers to prosthetic design. A distinguishing characteristic of our design is its robustness, and how well it handles “noise,” by which we mean any deviation from the norm in the building process or usage. The design can be successfully produced with a wide range of 3D printers, including fairly low-cost printers. Similarly, pieces can be made too big or too small by quite a wide margin and still function well, while the flexibility of the arm interface allows it to fit snugly on a variety of arm sizes. These factors lie at the core of the Universal Socket Prosthetic’s value: it represents a truly flexible, accessible prosthetic design system for anyone in the world.

Akhilesh Mishra: Design
Stephen Shelnutt: Testing
Hunter Garnier: Prototyping

title: Prusa i3 Mk2S print fan duct/nozzle

description.text:
A fan duct that spits out the air both from the sides and from the front. The "arms" that ducts air to the sides are made to immitate a flow-optimized design with large curves and an internal rib to guide the air but no CFD analysis has been done to prove the design.

Made to be printed upright with the side where the screw is inserted facing down. The uploaded version has a few more vertical supports for the "arms" than shown in the picture to prevent sagging of overhanging. Because it is so thin, all of the vertical surfaces act as bridges and prints well without slicer-generated support. The support columns in the part can easyly be removed with a knife after printing.

This has been made of PLA in 0,15mm layer height by myself.

The openings have been made from measurements taken from a part uploaded by "PJR" on the Prusa forums.

V4 version has a more print-friendly underside as it is flat against the print bed all the way until it can have a 45 degree print angle. Also, it has 12mm wide "arms" rather than 10mm which is the widest it can be without interferring with the P.I.N.D.A probe and the outlets has been moved a bit away from the hotend to allow clearance for a silicone sock.
The wider "arms" may lower air speed at the outlet but it seems that the flow is still pretty high.
